Geometric group theory studies algebraic objects (groups) by visualizing them as sets of transformations of geometric objects (metric spaces). In 1980s, Gromov revolutionized the field by introducing the notion of a hyperbolic space and outlining a broad program of study of isometry groups of such spaces. Intensive work in this direction has resulted in the rich theory of hyperbolic and relatively hyperbolic groups. 

A further generalization, the class of acylindrically hyperbolic groups, was suggested by the PI. It received considerable attention in the papers of the PI and others over the past few years. This class is broad enough to include many new examples of interest, yet a significant part of the theory of hyperbolic and relatively hyperbolic groups can be generalized in this context.

Results obtained by the PI lay the foundation of the theory of acylindrically hyperbolic group and provide new examples. The major achievements of the PI include

1) the proof of the equivalence of various definitions of acylindrically hyperbolic groups;

2) the general classification of acylindrical group actions on hyperbolic spaces;

3) a sufficient condition for a group acting on a tree to be acylindrically hyperbolic (joint result with A. Minasyan), which allowed the PI to provide new examples of acylindrically hyperbolic groups;

4) the study of transitivity degree of groups of geometric origin based on acylindrical hyperbolicity (join with M. Hull); in particular, this includes solutions of several open problems about highly transitive actions posed by Galssner;

5) linking analytic properties of finitely presented groups to the existence of nice actions on hyperbolic spaces.



